Thought: <atomic> I need to understand where astropy's CDS unit parser lives so I can locate and fix the bug causing incorrect unit ordering when multiple divisions are present.
Action: {"name": "Bash", "args": {"command": "find / -name 'cds.py' -path '*/astropy/*' 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}
Confidence: 72

Thought: <atomic> While that runs, let me also search for astropy's unit format files using Python to find the installed package location.
Action: {"name": "Bash", "args": {"command": "python3 -c \"import astropy; print(astropy.__file__)\" 2>/dev/null || uv run python -c \"import astropy; print(astropy.__file__)\" 2>/dev/null"}}
Confidence: 80

Thought: <atomic> Astropy isn't installed here. I need to find the astropy source on disk — let me search more broadly for its unit format module.
Action: {"name": "Bash", "args": {"command": "find /usr /opt ~/.local ~/Library 2>/dev/null -name 'cds.py' -path '*/units/format/*' | head -10"}}
Confidence: 65

Thought: <atomic> Astropy doesn't appear to be installed. I'll look at the GitHub source directly using web search to find the CDS unit parser and the bug location.
Action: {"name": "WebSearch", "args": {"query": "astropy CDS unit parser multiple division bug site:github.com astropy/astropy"}}
Confidence: 70

Thought: <atomic> Let me search for the astropy CDS unit format source to understand how multiple divisions are parsed, which is where the ordering bug originates.
Action: {"name": "WebSearch", "args": {"query": "astropy units format cds.py parse unit multiple division order bug github"}}
Confidence: 75
